In article <jktaberCMJ2E0.8qy@netcom.com>, jktaber@netcom.com (John K. Taber) writes:
> The effect of Colin James the Third's communications has been to kill
> discussion of ciphers that may not be very strong but that I thought
> are interesting.  At least it has been chilling upon me.
> 
> Does the law permit public discussion of patent details, because I would
> like help understanding his patent?  I read it, but I just don't understand
> how it covers the ciphers we have been discussing.

The law not only permits discussion of patent details, it positively
encourages it.  The *purpose* of a patent -- that is, the reason that
the government grants the patent-holder a monopoly -- is precisely
in exchange for publication so that others may be educated.
